node.text:
The London Contemporary Orchestra performing Isobel Waller-Bridge’s Arise at the Alexander McQueen Spring/Summer 2020 show.
As part of our #McQueenCreators series we will be sharing #McQueenMusic with you.

Visit our Spotify channel to hear playlists inspired by Alexander McQueen shows and featuring their soundtracks. 
Follow the link in our bio to listen to our #McQueenMusic playlists.

The Alexander McQueen Autumn/Winter 2020 show in Paris. “The collection is a love letter to women and to families, colleagues and friends. We went to Wales and were inspired by the warmth of its artistic and poetic heritage, by its folklore and the soul of its craft. The woman is courageous, grounded, bold: heroic. There is a sense of protection in the clothes, of safety and comfort, evoked through quilting and blankets. The hearts are a symbol of togetherness, of being there for others.” Sarah Burton Creative Director 
#McQueenAW20 #PFW #AlexanderMcQueen

node.text:
Follow Head of Atelier, Judy Halil, as she gives a step-by-step demonstration and insight into the expertise of the studio at Alexander McQueen.

Here she makes one of the centrepieces of the Roses installation: the swirling red Rose dress by Sarah Burton from the Autumn/Winter 2019 collection.

Visit the installation at #27OldBondStreet, our London flagship.

Video by @MashaVasyukova.

#AlexanderMcQueen

node.text:
The Autumn/Winter 2021 collection, #McQueenAnemones.⁣
⁣
Luca wears an anemone print flower dress with exploded sleeves in rose gold poly faille.⁣
⁣
See the #McQueenAW21 collection via the link in bio.⁣
⁣
Photographed by #PaoloRoversi.⁣
Art directed by @mmparisdotcom.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Alexander McQueen on August 11, 2021 tagging @alexandermcqueen.

node.text:
#McQueenRoses: An embroidered hessian dress from the Autumn/Winter 2003 Scanners collection.⁣
⁣
Lee Alexander McQueen imagined tribes of women struggling against the elements on an epic journey to create Scanners, his Paris show of Autumn/Winter 2003.⁣
⁣
In his mind, it created a tundra where migrating cultures met, merged and swapped traditions in a brutally extreme climate.⁣
⁣
One dress on that journey was molded from hessian, and naively embroidered with wool flowers, butterflies and insects.⁣
⁣
See the installation at #27OldBondStreet, our London flagship.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Alexander McQueen on August 10, 2021. May be an image of flower.

node.text:
Lee Alexander McQueen embedded the form and colour of flowers, real and imagined, into the making of the Sarabande collection. Elevated and couture-like, the show was McQueen at his most romantic — and it ended with the unforgettable finale of a corset-framed dress which he had filled with fresh hydrangeas and roses. ⁣
⁣
“The dress was meant to be covered and wrapped in twisted tulle like other pieces in the collection... but just as it was about to go out, Lee took scissors and — it was so incredible — had the bravery to just hack off the tulle and then spray it with cobweb spray... It was so immediate and so alive.”- Sarah Burton.⁣
⁣
#McQueenRoses at #27OldBondStreet, our London flagship.⁣
⁣
Photographed by @ChloeLeDrezen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Alexander McQueen on August 10, 2021 tagging @alexandermcqueen. May be an image of rose, prairie gentian and indoor.

node.text:
Restoring the finale dress from the Sarabande collection for the #McQueenRoses installation at #27OldBondStreet, our London flagship.

During restoration, under more permanent silk flowers, a real bud from the original Sarabande finale dress was preserved and uncovered.

Florist Phyllida Holbeach had gathered dried and fresh flower research from New Covent Garden Flower Market and travelled from London to finish the dress with Lee Alexander McQueen and the team moments before the show began. 

“The flowers were real, they couldn’t be put on until about an hour before the show, so it was all incredibly organic and immediate.” - Sarah Burton.

Photographed by @ChloeLeDrezen.

A finale dress from the Spring/Summer 2007 Sarabande collection.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The collection stemmed from a lyrical stream of consciousness about a ‘decadent and decaying grandeur’, which McQueen wanted to manifest against the backdrop of a ‘deserted theatre.’⁣⁣
⁣⁣

node.text:
The #McQueenRoses installation, open at #27OldBondStreet, our London flagship.⁣
⁣
Creative Director, Sarah Burton, has curated a garden of flower narratives which begins with the juxtaposition of two spectacular dresses: her Red Rose dress of Autumn/Winter 2019, and the floral finale dress Lee Alexander McQueen made for Sarabande in Spring/Summer 2007.⁣
⁣
The installation unfolds into an examination of the technical feats and the back and forth between present and past, nature and craft which have blossomed into so many varieties over time.⁣
⁣
Video by @MashaVasyukova.

node.text:
“Front and foremost in this collection was the idea of the pollination of flowers and the work that bees do... about the natural world and the importance of it and the significance of it.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
If it all disappears, then nature is gone, and we’re all gone as well.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The idea of the nature that bees and flowers create became magnified, flowers and honeycombs exploded on a huge scale.⁣
⁣
The honeycomb dresses represented the rigour of the beehive itself and how they are constructed... all the smocking was done by hand and the shapes exploded out from the smocking…” - Sarah Burton.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
The Bees collection can be seen at #McQueenRoses installation at #27OldBondStreet, our London flagship.⁣

node.text:
The Queen Bee dress from Sarah Burton’s Spring/Summer 2013 collection.

“The gold dress represents the honey and the hive...it has a hip cage underneath it, all the silhouettes are emphasising the female form, so she has a waist and an exaggerated hip.

She has a hip cage underneath her skirt and one over the top of it as well, so that’s the honey and beehive together.” - Sarah Burton.

The embroidered cage is adorned with goldwork techniques, 3-D flower applique, gold thread and beadwork.

#McQueenRoses open at #27OldBondStreet.

Photographed by @ChloeLedrezen.
